faq:
  - q: "What is a fractional operations partner?"
    a: "A fractional operations partner is one senior operator who covers the blended scope most founders actually need: executive support (calendar, inbox, board prep), chief-of-staff discipline (leadership cadence, decision logs, strategic initiatives), and operations management (SLA systems, dashboards, onboarding), part-time, remotely, under one engagement instead of three hires."
  - q: "How is an operations partner different from an executive assistant?"
    a: "Scope and authority. An EA operates the executive's day. An operations partner operates the executive's day and the systems around it: they'll run your calendar in the morning and redesign the team's SLA tracker in the afternoon. One of my clients put it directly: 'He's more than an assistant; he's a true operations partner.'"
  - q: "What does a fractional operations partner cost?"
    a: "Less than any one of the three full-time roles it replaces. Engagements run as monthly retainers scaled to hours and scope, agreed in the discovery call. As a Nairobi-based senior operator, my rates sit well below US/UK equivalents at the same seniority."
  - q: "What stage of company needs an operations partner?"
    a: "Founder-led companies from roughly 5 to 80 people, past the stage where the founder can hold everything in their head, before the stage where separate EA, chief-of-staff, and ops-manager hires are each justified. It's also the right model during transitions: post-fundraise, market entry, or rapid team scaling."
  - q: "Can the engagement evolve into a chief of staff or ops manager role?"
    a: "Yes, that's the normal path. Engagements start broad, then concentrate where your bottleneck is. Some clients narrow me into chief-of-staff scope, others into systems work. The format flexes; the operator stays the same."
